definition.value: A benzenediol that consists of hydroquinone bearing a single chloro substituent.
An amino aldehyde obtained by partial reduction of the carboxy group of L-histidine
A  fluorobenzoyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of 4-fluorobenzoic acid.
A dTDP-sugar having 3-dehydro-6-deoxy-alpha-D-glucose as the sugar component.
An extended flavonoid that is 6,7-methylenedioxyflavanone substituted by methoxy groups at positions 5 and 2' respectively.
A heteroglycan consisting of a mannan backbone with galactose side groups.
A 3-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is butanoic acid in which the hydrogens at position 2 are replaced by an acetyl and a hydroxy group (the S enantiomer).
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is acrylic acid in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a hydroxy group and a hydrogen at position 3 is substituted by a 4-hydroxyphenyl group.
A leucoanthocyanidin that is the 3-deoxy derivative of (2R,3S,4S)-leucocyanidin.
A glycosyloxyflavone that consists of flavonol attached to a D-xylosyl-D-glucosyl residue at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A polyprenylbenzoquinone that is fumigatin which is substituted by an all-trans-octaprenyl group at position 6.
A fatty acid anion 10:0 that is the conjugate base of decanoic acid.
A dimethoxyflavone  that is the 7,4'-dimethyl ether derivative of apigenin.

A sialotetraosylceramide consisting of a branched heptasaccharide made up from three sialyl residues, two galactose residues, one N-acetylglucosamine residue and a glucose residue at the reducing end attached to the ceramide portion via a beta-linkage.
An undecaprenyldiphospho-N-acetyl-(N-acetylglucosaminyl)muramoyl peptide in which the peptide element is L-alanyl-D-gamma-glutamyl-L-lysyl-D-alanyl-D-alanine.
A member of the class of phytosterols that is stigmast-5-ene substituted by a beta-hydroxy group at position 3.

A dipeptide resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of taurine with the gamma-carboxy group of L-glutamic acid. It was initially found in the parathyroid in 1980 and later in the brain of mammals.
A 3-enoyl-CoA in which the beta C=C double bond has trans stereochemistry.

A tetracycline used for treatment of infections caused by a variety of Gram positive and Gram negative microorganisms including Mycoplasma pneumoniae, Pasteurella pestis, Escherichia coli, Haemophilus influenzae (respiratory infections), and Diplococcus pneumoniae.
An S-substituted glutathione that is glutathione in which the hydrogen of the thiol has been replaced by a hexyl group (PDB entry: 1PN9).
An optically active form of vernolic acid having (12S,13R)-configuration.
An amino disaccharide consisting of beta-D-galactose linked via a (1->3)-glycosidic bond to N-acetyl-D-glucosamine.
A  dialkyl phosphate having ethyl as the alkyl group.
An ethyl sulfide compound having two ethyl groups attached to a sulfur atom.

The intermediate in the biosynthesis of vitamin B12 from uroporphyrinogen III in which three methyl groups have been introduced at positions 2, 7 and 20 of the tetrapyrrole framework and in which the carboxymethyl group at position 2 has been oxidised to form a lactone ring.

A member of the class of 1-thio-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholines that is (2S)-2-amino-3-sulfanylpropyl 2-(trimethylazaniumyl)ethyl phosphate in which the amino group is substituted by a palmitoyl group and the thiol is substituted by a palmityl group. It is a reversible inhibitor of secretory phospholipase A2.
A member of the class of pyrimidodiazepine 3,7,8,9-tetrahydropyrimido[4,5-b][1,4]diazepin-4-one bearing amino and acetyl substituents at positions 2 and 6 respectively.
A chlorocatechol that is catechol in which the hydrogen adjacent to one of the hydroxy groups is replaced by a chlorine.
A C19-gibberellin, initially identified in Gibberella fujikuroi.

A glycooctaosylceramide in which the sugar component is a linear heptasaccharide comprised of fucose, galactose, N-acetylgalactosamine, glucose and N-acetylglucosamine residues, branched with an extra L-fucosyl residue at one of the central galactose residues within the chain.
A GDP-sugar having 4-dehydro-6-deoxy-L-mannose as the sugar component.
A methylbenzyl alcohol that is toluene in which one of the ortho hydrogens has been replaced by a hydroxymethyl group.

A trihydroxyflavanone in which the three hydroxy substituents are located at positions 3', 4' and 7. It is found in Acacia mearnsii, Vernonia anthelmintica and Dalbergia odorifera and has a protective affect against oxidative stress-induced mitochondrial dysfunction.
